^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Jenny does technically have a pass and many players would pass. However, she has a pretty good hand. On average, when you are in 3rd seat, and there are 2 passes, the average number of HCP between the first 2 bidders is around 16 or so. Jenny has 6, so on average, the first 3 hands will have around 24 or so (16 + 6) which means Liz is likely to have a pretty good hand. |
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|It so  happens on this hand, both Don and I have max passes. But, even so, Liz still has an opening hand. So, your job in 3rd seat, when you know their side has the majority of the points, is to make it difficult for them by preempting if you can. Therefore, even experts who prefer disciplined preempts in 1st and 2nd position (misguided :) :) will preempt with light hands in 3rd seat. In fact, you should even preempt when you have close to an opener if it is appropriate.|
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|And you should preempt a weak 2 with a 5 card suit if you have good distribution (a singleton or void). And favorable vulnerability (you not vul, they vul) makes a preempt even more likely to be a good bid. Most experts would open 2@H in 3rd seat with Jenny's hand, even if they would not in 1st or 2nd seat. Although I don't particularly like opening light at the 1-level, I do like to preempt in 3rd seat.|
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


